<subSubSection id="C32E657E3C088A363E9B509EFD50FB07" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A363E9B509EFEAFFB4C" blockId="6.[160,1156,766,860]" box="[160,285,766,791]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363E9B509EFEAFFB4C" bold="true" box="[160,285,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A363E9B5142FD50FB07" blockId="6.[160,1156,766,860]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363FAB5142FE4CFB61" box="[400,510,802,826]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363FAB5142FE4CFB61" box="[400,510,802,826]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, refers to the possible ant model 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363DB05142FF7EFB07" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363DB05142FF7EFB07" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Pseudomyrmex triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the possible host tree 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363C315124FD6EFB07" box="[522,732,836,860]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Triplaris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363C315124FD6EFB07" box="[522,732,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Triplaris americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32E657E3C088A373E9B51E9FD44FA7F" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="1469" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A363E9B51E9FEB4FBF9" blockId="6.[160,1156,905,1727]" box="[160,262,905,930]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363E9B51E9FEB4FBF9" bold="true" box="[160,262,905,930]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A363E9B51CDFE47FC29" blockId="6.[160,1156,905,1727]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363E9B51CDFE7EFB9E" authority="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger, 2018" authorityName="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2018" box="[160,460,941,965]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363E9B51CDFE7EFB9E" box="[160,460,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Pseudolepturges triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A273579C3C088A363FE151CDFD8AFB9E" box="[474,568,941,965]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be easily differentiated from the other two species in the genus by the general light orange-yellowish integument;the anterior fourth of the elytra with a transversal, yellowish-whitish band of pubescence, demarcated from the colour of the integument, narrowing at middle, and the posterior third covered with indistinct yellowish-whitish pubescence, not distinctly demarcated from the colour of the integument.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A363EFB561DFC4BFC81" blockId="6.[160,1156,905,1727]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
In 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363EE6561DFEF7FCCE" authorityName=", Monne &amp; Monne" authorityYear="2007" box="[221,325,1149,1173]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caesius">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363EE6561DFEF7FCCE" box="[221,325,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">P. caesius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the integument is dark brown, the anterior half of the elytra possesses a heart-shaped patch of grey pubescence with one additional patch at each side, and the posterior fourth of the elytra is covered by greyish pubescence (
<figureCitation id="130F2A703C088A363DB956A2FC5EFC81" box="[898,1004,1218,1242]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[160,225,676,699]" captionTargetBox="[163,1152,142,646]" captionTargetId="figure-1@5.[163,1152,142,646]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Comparison between Pseudolepturges triplarinus sp. nov., Pseudolepturges rufulus (Bates) and Pseudolepturges caesius Monné &amp; Monné: (a,b) Pseudolepturges triplarinus sp. nov. holotype male: (a) head in lateral view; (b) anterior half of elytra; (c,d) Pseudolepturges rufulus (Bates), male; (a) head in lateral view; (b) anterior half of elytra. (e) Pseudolepturges caesius Monné &amp; Monné, holotype female, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174829/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Figure 3e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A363EFB5685FDD7FD3E" blockId="6.[160,1156,905,1727]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
In 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363EE55685FEF7FCA6" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[222,325,1253,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufulus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363EE55685FEF7FCA6" box="[222,325,1253,1277]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">P. rufulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the integument of the head, pronotum and proximal third of the elytra are red, the remaining integument of the elytra is dark brown. The elytra have in the anterior third and posterior fourth a transversal, narrow band of whitish pubescence, the anterior one can be with a side branch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C088A373EFB570FFC0FF892" blockId="6.[160,1156,905,1727]" lastBlockId="7.[160,1156,142,548]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="1469" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363EFB570FFE54FDDC" authority="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger, 2018" authorityName="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2018" box="[192,486,1391,1415]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363EFB570FFE54FDDC" box="[192,486,1391,1415]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Pseudolepturges triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A273579C3C088A363FD6570FFDF7FDDC" box="[493,581,1391,1415]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363CEE570FFC88FDDC" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[725,826,1391,1415]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufulus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363CEE570FFC88FDDC" box="[725,826,1391,1415]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">P. rufulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also by the longer lower eye lobes, about 1.8 times the gena length (
<figureCitation id="130F2A703C088A363C4A57F2FD6FFDF1" box="[625,733,1426,1450]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1455,1478]" captionTargetBox="[163,1151,142,1424]" captionTargetId="figure-26@4.[163,1152,142,1424]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Comparison between Pseudolepturges triplarinus sp. nov. and Pseudolepturges rufulus (Bates): (a,b,c,g) P. triplarinus sp. nov. holotype male; (a) dorsal view, (b) ventral view; (c) lateral view; (g) frontal view. (d,e,f,h) P. rufulus, male; (d) dorsal view; (e) ventral view; (f) lateral view; (h) frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174827/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">
Figure 
<quantity id="4CCC9B103C088A363CFA57F2FD6FFDF1" box="[705,733,1426,1450]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" unit="g" value="2.0">2g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363D2957F2FCCBFDF1" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[786,889,1426,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufulus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363D2957F2FCCBFDF1" box="[786,889,1426,1450]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">P. rufulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the lower ocular lobes are about 0.7 times the gena length (
<figureCitation id="130F2A703C088A363C7B57D5FD1BFD96" box="[576,681,1461,1485]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[160,225,1455,1478]" captionTargetBox="[163,1151,142,1424]" captionTargetId="figure-26@4.[163,1152,142,1424]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. Comparison between Pseudolepturges triplarinus sp. nov. and Pseudolepturges rufulus (Bates): (a,b,c,g) P. triplarinus sp. nov. holotype male; (a) dorsal view, (b) ventral view; (c) lateral view; (g) frontal view. (d,e,f,h) P. rufulus, male; (d) dorsal view; (e) ventral view; (f) lateral view; (h) frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174827" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174827/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Figure 2h</figureCitation>
). Although 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA54B043C088A363D1557D5FC67FD96" author="Gilmour EF" box="[814,981,1461,1485]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" pagination="3 - 36" refId="ref3674" refString="Gilmour EF. 1957. On the neotropical Acanthocinini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Lamiinae). Some new genera and species. Arquivos de Biologia e Tecnologia. 10 (1): 3 - 36." type="journal article" year="1957">Gilmour (1957)</bibRefCitation>
has mentioned the small lower eye lobes as a generic feature, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA54B043C088A363C9157B7FC7FFDB4" author="Monne MA &amp; Monne ML" box="[682,973,1495,1519]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" pagination="1038 - 1042" refId="ref3992" refString="Monne MA, Monne ML. 2007. New species of neotropical Acanthocinini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Braisileira de Zoologia. 24 (4): 1038 - 1042." type="journal article" year="2007">Monné and Monné (2007)</bibRefCitation>
do not mention it (translated): ‘The characters that distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363C85579AFCDDFE49" authorityName="Gilmour" authorityYear="1957" box="[702,879,1530,1554]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C088A363C85579AFCDDFE49" box="[702,879,1530,1554]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468">Pseudolepturges</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other Neotropical genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C088A363F22547DFE01FE6E" box="[281,435,1565,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Acanthocinini">Acanthocinini</taxonomicName>
with elytra lacking erect setae are: elytra lacking centro-basal crest and without lateral carinae, prothorax with parallel sides and lateral tubercle placed at posterior third, pronotum without tubercles, sulcus at base of pronotum interrupted by the insertion of the tubercles, antennae with 11 antenomeres and the first metatarsomere longer than the next two’. Perhaps this is due to the variation of the size of the eye lobes in several other genera and most probably this is a specific characteristic, as 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373F5952D1FDA1F892" authorityName="Gilmour" authorityYear="1957" box="[354,531,177,201]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373F5952D1FDA1F892" box="[354,531,177,201]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Pseudolepturges</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally created as monotypic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C098A373EFB52B4FCD5F9C2" blockId="7.[160,1156,142,548]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">
The individual of 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373FB052B4FD01F8B7" authority="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger, 2018" authorityName="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2018" box="[395,691,212,236]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373FB052B4FD01F8B7" box="[395,691,212,236]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Pseudolepturges triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A273579C3C098A373C8752B4FCA7F8B7" box="[700,789,212,236]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
was observed on the damaged stem of a 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373F2D5296FE5BF955" box="[278,489,246,270]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Triplaris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373F2D5296FE5BF955" box="[278,489,246,270]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Triplaris americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tree, running in close proximity to ants of 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373DE45296FEC4F96A" authority="Weddell" authorityName="Weddell" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373DE45296FEBCF96A" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Pseudomyrmex triplarinus</emphasis>
Weddell
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="130F2A703C098A373FB25379FE59F96A" box="[393,491,281,305]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="5.[159,224,1572,1595]" captionTargetBox="[162,1151,937,1541]" captionTargetId="figure-62@5.[162,1151,937,1541]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 4. Habitat of Pseudolepturges triplarinus sp. nov. and its potential ant model Pseudomyrmex triplarinus Weddell: (a) Trees of Triplaris americana (L.) Pav. Ex Meisn. (indicated by white arrows). (b) Ants of Pseudomyrmex triplarinus on the stem of T. americana." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174831" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174831/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(b)). When the second author approached to collect the beetle manually, the ants emerged from the tree internodes and came closer. Although both, the second author and the ants represented a threat for the beetle, it proceeded to run between the ants without being attacked by the latter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B36F53C098A373EFB53C4FD44FA7F" blockId="7.[160,1156,142,548]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">
The about similar body length (workers of 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373CF853C4FC50F9E7" box="[707,994,420,444]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373CF853C4FC50F9E7" box="[707,994,420,444]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Pseudomyrmex triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a body length of 5.35 ± 
<quantity id="4CCC9B103C098A373F5453A6FE6BF985" box="[367,473,454,478]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" unit="mm" value="0.44">0.44 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373FD353A6FE44F985" box="[488,502,454,478]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">n</emphasis>
= 25), the colour (compare 
<figureCitation id="130F2A703C098A373D7553A6FC09F985" box="[846,955,454,478]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="5.[159,224,1572,1595]" captionTargetBox="[162,1151,937,1541]" captionTargetId="figure-62@5.[162,1151,937,1541]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 4. Habitat of Pseudolepturges triplarinus sp. nov. and its potential ant model Pseudomyrmex triplarinus Weddell: (a) Trees of Triplaris americana (L.) Pav. Ex Meisn. (indicated by white arrows). (b) Ants of Pseudomyrmex triplarinus on the stem of T. americana." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174831" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174831/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Figures 4</figureCitation>
(b) and 2(a)), the behaviour and the close co-occurrence suggest that 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373CC75389FB91FA5A" authority="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger, 2018" authorityName="de L. Nascimento &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2018" box="[764,1059,489,513]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pseudolepturges" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373CC75389FB91FA5A" box="[764,1059,489,513]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Pseudolepturges triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A273579C3C098A373A105389FB36FA5A" box="[1067,1156,489,513]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
imitates 
<taxonomicName id="4C344D763C098A373F39506CFDAFFA7F" box="[258,541,524,548]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pseudomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplarinus">
<emphasis id="B940EAE73C098A373F39506CFDAFFA7F" box="[258,541,524,548]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1469">Pseudomyrmex triplarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(discussed below).
</paragraph>
